        'route' => '/blog/retirement-corpus-guide/',
        'slug' => 'blog__retirement-corpus-guide',
        'title' => 'How Much Money Do You Need to Retire?',
        'description' => 'Stop guessing your retirement number. Learn how to calculate your inflation-adjusted corpus requirement.',
        'category' => 'Blog',
        'type' => 'post',
        'content' => '<h2>How Much Money Do You Need to Retire?</h2>
<p>The 25x Rule (and why it might fail)</p>
<p>Step-by-Step Calculation</p>
<p>Where to Invest for Retirement?</p>
<p>Check Your Number</p>
<p>The biggest financial mistake people make is underestimating inflation. A million dollars today won&#x27;t be worth a million dollars in 20 years.</p>
<p>Get your personalized target.</p>
<p>A popular rule says you need 25 times your annual expenses to retire. So if you spend $40,000/year, you need $1 Million. This is based on the &quot;4% Safe Withdrawal Rate&quot;.</p>
<p>The Catch: This rule assumes a 30-year retirement. With increasing life expectancy (living to 90 or 95), you might run out of money.</p>
<p>Retirement is a long game. You cannot rely solely on safe assets like FDs or Bonds. You need Equity (Stocks) to beat inflation during the accumulation phase. As you get closer to retirement, slowly shift to safer debt instruments.</p>
<p>Estimate Current Expenses: Only count what will persist in retirement (no EMI, no child education fees).</p>
<p>Adjust for Inflation: Formula: Future Expense = Current * (1 + Rate)^Years. Example: $50,000 today becomes $90,000 in 20 years at 3% inflation.</p>
<p>Calculate Corpus: Divide annual future expense by your withdrawal rate (e.g., 3% or 4%).</p>',
    ],
    [
        'route' => '/blog/sip-vs-lumpsum/',
        'slug' => 'blog__sip-vs-lumpsum',
        'title' => 'SIP vs Lumpsum: Which is Better for You?',
        'description' => 'Compare Systematic Investment Plans (SIP) with Lumpsum investing. Understand the pros and cons of each strategy for mutual funds.',
        'category' => 'Blog',
        'type' => 'post',
        'content' => '<h2>SIP vs Lumpsum: Which Strategy Wins?</h2>
<p>What is SIP (Systematic Investment Plan)?</p>
<p>What is Lumpsum Investing?</p>
<p>Comparison Table</p>
<p>Verdict</p>
<p>Calculate Your Returns</p>
<p>Benefits of SIP</p>
<p>Benefits of Lumpsum</p>
<p>Investing in mutual funds is one of the best ways to create wealth. But the big question remains: Should you invest a small amount every month (SIP) or a large amount at once (Lumpsum)?</p>
<p>Model both SIP and Lumpsum scenarios.</p>
<p>SIP is a method where you invest a fixed sum regularly (usually monthly) in a mutual fund scheme. It is similar to a Recurring Deposit (RD) but for market-linked investments.</p>
<p>Lumpsum is a one-time investment. This is usually done when you receive a bonus, windfall, or sale of an asset.</p>
<p>If you have a regular salary, **SIP is the best route**. It automates your savings and reduces risk. If you have a large sum of money sitting idle, invest it via **Lumpsum**, but consider doing it in tranches (STP) if you fear a market crash.</p>
<p>Rupee Cost Averaging: You buy more units when the market is down and fewer when it&#x27;s up, averaging your cost.</p>
<p>Discipline: Forces you to save money before you spend it.</p>
<p>No Market Timing: You don&#x27;t need to worry if the market is at a peak or a bottom.</p>
<p>Higher Potential Returns: If invested during a market dip, your money grows for the entire duration.</p>
<p>Convenience: One-time transaction.</p>',
    ],
    [
        'route' => '/blog/snowball-vs-avalanche/',
        'slug' => 'blog__snowball-vs-avalanche',
        'title' => 'Snowball vs Avalanche: Which Debt Strategy is Best?',
        'description' => 'Compare Dave Ramsey\\',
        'category' => 'Blog',
        'type' => 'post',
        'content' => '<h2>Debt Snowball vs Avalanche: The Ultimate Showdown</h2>
<p>The Debt Snowball (Behavioral Approach)</p>
<p>The Debt Avalanche (Mathematical Approach)</p>
<p>Which one should you pick?</p>
<p>Create Your Plan</p>
<p>Getting out of debt is 20% math and 80% behavior. The strategy you choose depends on what motivates you more: logic or emotion.</p>
<p>Simulate both strategies now.</p>
<p>Popularized by Dave Ramsey, this method focuses on momentum.</p>
<p>Why it works: You get quick wins. Eliminating a small credit card bill in month 1 feels amazing and keeps you going.</p>
<p>This method focuses on efficiency.</p>
<p>Why it works: You pay less interest overall. A 24% credit card hurts more than a 5% student loan.</p>
<p>If you need motivation and often quit diets/plans, pick Snowball. If you are disciplined and hate losing money to banks, pick Avalanche.</p>
<p>List debts from smallest balance to largest (ignore interest rates).</p>
<p>Pay minimums on everything except the smallest.</p>
<p>Throw every extra dollar at the smallest debt until it is gone.</p>
<p>Roll that payment into the next smallest debt.</p>
<p>List debts from highest interest rate to lowest.</p>
<p>Pay minimums on everything except the highest rate debt.</p>
<p>Attack the high-interest debt first.</p>',
